result.execSummary:
The defendant Jessica Elaine Corbett was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Forgery-Uttering, a class H felony, Wisconsin Statutes 943.38(2).

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

records.addlTxt:
Defendant Jessica Elaine Corbett in court with attorney Matthew V Plummer.  Defendant Jessica Elaine Corbett in custody.  Patrick J Anderson appeared for the State of Wisconsin.
Case in court for plea/sentencing.  Parties have reached an agreement.  Plea negotiations set forth on the record and agreed upon by the parties.

AS TO COUNT 1:
Defendant changes plea to GUILTY.  Defendant examined as to plea, advised of Constitutional Rights and the maximum penalties.  Defendant further advised that if not a US citizen, deportation is possible.  Court found that the defendant knowingly, voluntarily and intelligently waived rights.  Plea Questionnaire/Waiver of Rights form, Addendum, and Elements/Jury Instructions received and filed.  Parties stipulate to the Criminal Complaint as a factual basis to sustain defendant's plea.  Court found defendant GUILTY and ordered a Judgment of Conviction be entered on the record.  

Pursuant to plea negotiations and on the motion of the State, Court ordered COUNTS 2 AND 3 DISMISSED BUT READ IN for the purpose of sentencing.  

Court advised the defendant that as a convicted felon, she may never own or possess a firearm.  Court advised defendant that she may not vote until her civil rights have been restored.  Sentencing proceeded.

...
Statements made by the State, Defense Counsel, and Defendant.

AS TO COUNT 1:
The Court sentenced the defendant to 9 MONTHS in the House of Correction, CONSECUTIVE to any other sentence, with credit for 3 days time served. 


The Court STAYED the sentence and placed the defendant on probation for 18 MONTHS.

CONDITIONS OF PROBATION: 
- 10 DAYS condition time in the House of Correction.
- Standard conditions. 
- AODA assessment and cooperate with any recommended treatment.
- Provide DNA sample.
- Cooperate with any mental health assessments deemed appropriate by the department. 


Court set restitution at $2,000.00 payable to TriCity National Bank.  Court ordered the defendant to pay all mandatory court costs, fees, and surcharges (including DNA) by the end of supervision.  Failure to pay shall result in a civil judgment.  Court waived all non-mandatory court costs, fees, and surcharges.

20 day appeal rights given.
